Objective
----------------------------------------------------------------
Identify the "main" ataman depicted at the base of the famous
monument in the center of Krasnodar, Russia, and submit their
name in the correct format.

Tools Used
----------------------------------------------------------------
- Google Search
- Wikipedia (English and Russian)
- Visual analysis of the challenge image

Steps
----------------------------------------------------------------
1. Read the challenge. It mentions a beautiful monument in the
   center of Krasnodar with three atamans at its base. The hint
   says "read the history." Flag format is KUBSTU{FirstName_LastName}
   and shown in Cyrillic as KUBSTU{Имя_Фамилия}.

2. Downloaded the attached image (image_2.png). It showed the
   Catherine II monument in central Krasnodar. Three bronze
   Cossack figures stand at the base. The name "АНТОН" (Anton)
   is visibly inscribed on the plinth.

3. Searched Google for the monument and identified the three
   Black Sea Cossack leaders depicted:
      - Zakhary Chepega  -- Kosh Ataman (chief rank)
      - Anton Golovaty   -- Military judge, negotiated with Catherine
      - Sidor Bely       -- First commander of the Cossack Host

4. Determined that Zakhary Chepega held the highest title:
   Kosh Ataman, making him the "main" one. Confirmed on the
   Russian Wikipedia page: full name is
   Захарий Алексеевич Чепега.

5. Attempted multiple Latin transliterations -- all rejected:
      KUBSTU{Zakhary_Chepega}   -- incorrect
      KUBSTU{Zachary_Chepega}   -- incorrect
      KUBSTU{Zakhary_Chepiha}   -- incorrect
      KUBSTU{Zakhariy_Chepega}  -- incorrect

6. Noticed the flag format in the challenge was shown in Cyrillic
   (KUBSTU{Имя_Фамилия}). Switched to Cyrillic input:
      KUBSTU{Захарий_Чепега}   -- CORRECT

Key Takeaway
----------------------------------------------------------------
When a Russian CTF platform displays the flag format in Cyrillic,
always try Cyrillic input first. Latin transliterations will be
rejected even if historically accurate, because the platform
does exact string matching. The language of the format hint is
the language of the expected answer.

